The @Value annotation is used in the Spring framework to inject values into fields, methods or constructor parameters of a Spring bean from a property source. The values can be hardcoded, taken from a properties file, environment variable, system properties, or from any other source of configuration data.Here are some examples of how @Value can be used:Injecting a value into a field:kotlinCopy code@Component
public class MyComponent {

    @Value("${my.property}")
    private String myProperty;

    // ...
}
In this example, the value of the my.property property from a properties file or any other property source will be injected into the myProperty field of the MyComponent bean.Injecting a value into a method:typescriptCopy code@Component
public class MyComponent {

    private String myProperty;

    @Value("${my.property}")
    public void setMyProperty(String myProperty) {
        this.myProperty = myProperty;
    }

    // ...
}
In this example, the value of the my.property property will be injected into the setMyProperty method of the MyComponent bean.Injecting a value into a constructor parameter:kotlinCopy code@Component
public class MyComponent {

    private String myProperty;

    @Autowired
    public MyComponent(@Value("${my.property}") String myProperty) {
        this.myProperty = myProperty;
    }

    // ...
}
In this example, the value of the my.property property will be injected into the constructor of the MyComponent bean.Overall, @Value can be used to inject any type of value into a Spring bean, including strings, numbers, booleans, arrays, and more. It provides a flexible way to configure Spring beans based on the configuration data in the application.

In object-oriented programming, a reference is a variable that holds the memory address of an object in memory. A static reference and a non-static reference differ in the way they are used to access members (variables or methods) of a class.A non-static reference is an instance-level reference that is created for each instance (object) of a class. Non-static members are associated with each instance of the class and can be accessed using a non-static reference. Non-static references are created using the new keyword and are usually accessed through instance methods.Here is an example:javaCopy codepublic class MyClass {
    private int myVariable;

    public void setMyVariable(int value) {
        this.myVariable = value;
    }

    public int getMyVariable() {
        return myVariable;
    }
}

MyClass myInstance = new MyClass();
myInstance.setMyVariable(10);
int value = myInstance.getMyVariable(); // value = 10
In this example, myInstance is a non-static reference to an instance of MyClass. The setMyVariable and getMyVariable methods are instance methods, which means they can be accessed through the myInstance reference to set or get the value of the myVariable member.A static reference, on the other hand, is a class-level reference that is shared by all instances of a class. Static members are associated with the class itself and can be accessed using a static reference. Static references are created using the class name and are usually accessed through static methods.Here is an example:csharpCopy codepublic class MyClass {
    private static int myVariable;

    public static void setMyVariable(int value) {
        MyClass.myVariable = value;
    }

    public static int getMyVariable() {
        return MyClass.myVariable;
    }
}

MyClass.setMyVariable(10);
int value = MyClass.getMyVariable(); // value = 10
