The Logger class is a utility class in Java that is used to log messages and events from an application. It is part of the Java Logging API and is commonly used in enterprise applications, web applications, and other types of software.The Logger class provides methods for logging messages at different levels of severity, such as:SEVERE: for critical errors that cause the application to failWARNING: for non-critical errors or warnings that do not cause the application to failINFO: for informational messages that describe the application's state or progressCONFIG: for configuration messages that describe the application's configuration or setupFINE: for debugging messages that provide detailed information about the application's behaviorFINER and FINEST: for very detailed debugging messages that are rarely usedTo use the Logger class, you first need to obtain an instance of it using the getLogger method, passing in a string that identifies the name of the logger. Typically, the logger name is set to the fully-qualified class name of the class that is using the logger.Here's an example of using the Logger class to log a message:javaCopy codeimport java.util.logging.Logger;

