In C, you can print the client's address using the accept function, which is used to accept incoming connections on a socket. The accept function takes a listening socket as an argument and returns a new socket that is connected to the client. The address of the client is stored in a sockaddr structure, which can be accessed using the accept function. Here is an example:Copy code#include <sys/socket.h>
#include <netinet/in.h>
#include <arpa/inet.h>
#include <stdio.h>

int main() {
    int listener = socket(AF_INET, SOCK_STREAM, 0);
    // ... bind, listen, etc.

    struct sockaddr_in client_addr;
    socklen_t client_len = sizeof(client_addr);
    int client_socket = accept(listener, (struct sockaddr *)&client_addr, &client_len);

    char client_ip[INET_ADDRSTRLEN];
    inet_ntop(AF_INET, &client_addr.sin_addr, client_ip, INET_ADDRSTRLEN);
